<p><img height="56" src="Images/housing/blank.png" width="23" /> <img height="270" src="Images/housing/apply1.png" width="202" />&nbsp; <object style="width: 500px; height: 270px;" width="500" height="270" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/PXNoRDDoXSQ" /><embed style="width: 500px; height: 270px;" width="500" height="270" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/PXNoRDDoXSQ" /> </object> <img height="270" src="Images/housing/apply2.png" width="202" /></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>Husbands often spend so much time with their careers and Church callings that they inadvertently neglect their families. This is spiritually and socially dangerous-the Lord has commanded our generation to put our responsibilities to our families first, after the worship of God. In many households, both spouses work outside the home. In such cases, if the husband is not willing to share fairly with the wife the responsibilities of maintaining a home, the marriage suffers.</p>
<p>I know one bishop who scheduled his evening meetings at 9:00 P.M. so he could spend the time between 6:00 and 9:00 P.M. with his wife and children. He made sure that he spent every other Saturday exclusively with his <a href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a>. Over the years, he and his family have been rewarded a hundredfold for his investment of time, and his calling didn't suffer in the least.</p>
<p>On the other hand, many women neglect their marriages in favor of their children. Evidence now overwhelmingly tells us that parents who want to rear happy, well-adjusted children need to concentrate first on their marriage. A couple's love and service for each other will affect their children more positively than any other act they can perform. <strong>(It Takes Time </strong><strong>By </strong><a href="http://lds.org/ensign/1987/12/it-takes-time?lang=eng&amp;query=Quality+Time+couple#pop_001-03220_000_014"><strong>Dee W. Hadley</strong></a><strong> Dec 1987)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Questions to consider:</strong></p>
<p><strong>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>How could putting work or personal interests (such as Facebook, Pinterest, etc) above family affect the family in a negative way?</p>
<p><strong>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>How could spending quality time with family benefit? What effect could it have on the marriage relationship and relationships among the children?</p>
<p><strong>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong>What other hobbies or social media takes away from quality time with families?</p>
